TY  - JOUR
T1  - Potential Predictors of Whistle-Blowing: A Prosocial Behavior Perspective
AU  - Dozier, Janelle Brinker
AU  - Miceli, Marcia P.
Y1  - 1985/10/01
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1985.4279105
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1985.4279105
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 823
EP  - 836
VL  - 10
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Why do some observers of organizational wrongdoing choose to report it? This question has received little research attention despite its prominence in the popular media. This paper attempts to show that whistle-blowing is a form of prosocial behavior. Empirical studies in the social-psychological literature of prosocial behavior provide clues about personality and situational variables predictive of whistle-blowing. Latané's and Barley's (1968, 1970) bystander intervention framework is modified for whistle-blowing decisions. Propositions for future research are offered.
AB  - Why do some observers of organizational wrongdoing choose to report it? This question has received little research attention despite its prominence in the popular media. This paper attempts to show that whistle-blowing is a form of prosocial behavior. Empirical studies in the social-psychological literature of prosocial behavior provide clues about personality and situational variables predictive of whistle-blowing. Latané's and Barley's (1968, 1970) bystander intervention framework is modified for whistle-blowing decisions. Propositions for future research are offered.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1985.4279105
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1985.4279105
Y2  - 2026/04/24
